<DOC><DOCNO> AP880330-0161 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1543EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-US-Salvador     03-30 0176</FIRST><SECOND>AM-US-Salvador,170</SECOND><HEAD>US Assails Guerrilla Escalation Plan</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Plans by Salvadoran guerrillas to escalatetheir war against the U.S.-backed government reinforce their``well-deserved reputation for ruthless and indiscriminateviolence,'' the State Department said Wednesday.   The rebel plan was disclosed by the insurgents' high command ata news conference with foreign journalists in guerrilla-heldterritory. Among other steps, the rebels said they intend to targetU.S. military advisers for assassination.   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the United Statesobviously ``will not be intimidated by threats against itspersonnel. The U.S. commitment to assist the democratic governmentof El Salvador, backed by a strong bipartisan consensus, remainsfirm.''   The rebel leaders said they plan to increase attacks in SanSalvador, the capital, targeting the country's upper class, to usesurface-to-air missiles against military helicopers and to step upattacks against military installations.   Redman said the proposed rebel offensive ``once again confirmstheir disregard for the well-being of the Salvadoran people andtheir commitment to achieve power and install a totalitariandictatorship at any price.''</TEXT></DOC>